description:
Cobra, scientifically known as Naja naja, is one of the poisonous snake species native to the Indian subcontinent. It grows to an average height of 1 m and has two circular ocelli patterns on the rear of its hood. These patterns seem to be connected by a curved line, giving the look of spectacles. This is why the snake is also known as the Spectacled Cobra of India. A newborn cobra measures between 20 to 30 cm, but has fully functional venom glands. 

Mating Behavior 
Cobra snake lays its eggs during the period of April to July. The eggs, numbering between 12 and 30 eggs, are laid underground. The incubation period lasts for 48 to 69 days. 

Diet 
Spectacled Cobra of India survives on a diet consisting mainly of rodents. 

Natural Habitat
Cobra is usually found inhabiting open forests and farmlands of India. However, one may also see them in Indian cities, living in the sewers and underground drains. 

Relation with Indian Mythology 
Cobra snake is widely associated with Indian Hindu mythology. Lord Shiva is often portrayed with a protective cobra coiled around his neck. Lord Vishnu is usually represented as resting on the coiled body of Sheshnag, a snake deity with a number of cobra heads.

We came across this Cobra while walking along the canal at twilight. Luckily Yogesh spotted it a few feet ahead by seeing it move across the path. Somehow the Cobra would'nt slither away, and one reason as someone amongst us thought was the shadow of its hood in the torchlight (you may see it's facing away from us). I am not aware if snakes can perceive threat looking at shadows (obviously no body warmth there ;-)). It was supposedly, a threat posture, to display its hood. Whatever the reason, I had to climb the steep trench alongside the canal and walk across to face the cobra with my torchlight, which made the Cobra slither away and stopped hissing.

description: A rare documentation of cannibalism in the Indian/Spectacled Cobra (Naja Naja)!!! Both the predator and prey look like adult Indian cobras. My wife and I spotted it when the attack had already occurred and the prey had been partially swallowed. The two individuals stayed in this position for over an hour. I finally had to leave but I came back after two hours (around 8pm IST) and there was only one cobra visible then at the same location.

Does release of snakes far away from rescue area is helpful?
.
.
I deeply think that releasing the snake into it's nearby area from the Rescue spot will be helpful because that particular snake might have been living Their it's whole life and knows each and everything about that specific area. So i always prefer releasing a snake nearby from the rescue spot. People must understand about the snakes importance near our surroundings and thats how the rescuer must convince the local people and aware them in any way possible. just rescuing them and releasing far away doesn't work, now everyone must learn to live with snakes and also be more careful to avoid any conflicts.
 I suggest Releasing a snake at a appropriate habitat nearby from the rescue spot will increase the chance of its survival, and also they will keep an check on controlling the population of rodents, rats etc.

Sent by a relative. Time is approximate

The king cobra (Ophiophagus hannah) is a venomous snake species of elapids endemic to jungles in Southern and Southeast Asia. The sole member of the genus Ophiophagus, it is distinguishable from other cobras, most noticeably by its size and neck patterns. The king cobra is the world's longest venomous snake, with an average length of 3.18 to 4 m (10.4 to 13.1 ft),[2] reaching a maximum of 5.85 m (19.2 ft).[3] Its skin colour varies across the habitats, from black with white stripes to unbroken brownish grey. It preys chiefly on other snakes, including its own species. Unlike other snakes, it rarely hunts non-reptile vertebratessuch as rodents and lizards.

description:
Indian Spectacled Cobra
 (naja naja)
 Average length :- 100 cm.  (3 feet 3 inches)
 Maximum length :- 220 cm.  I.  (7 feet 3 inches)
 Color and Size :- Brown, yellowish, greyish or black.  The head is large.  Nakpudia big.  Eyes large and black, round iris.  Behind the fanya is the number ten in Moli script.  In some snakes this number is different.  Not in some.  Two black spots are visible on the inner side of the hood.
 Breeding :- Female lays 10-15 eggs between April and May.  The female incubates the eggs for about 60 days until the chicks hatch.  The length of the chicks is 25-30 cm.  I.  And venomous from birth.
 Food :- Tadpoles, frogs, mice and rarely small snakes.
 Found :- Everywhere in India.
 Habitat :- Forests, grassy areas, paddy fields, sand dunes and run-down houses.
 Characteristics :- This snake which is revered by Hindus is diurnal and nocturnal.  Fana is removed when Divac is gone.  It has binocular vision due to its small mouth.
